  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Meyer's NT Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 15:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Both of these appearances also are otherwise unknow.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ἰακώβῳ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The non-addition of any distinguishing epithet makes it more than probable that the person meant is he who was then the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "James",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κατʼ ἐξοχήν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", James the Just,[30] not one of the Twelve, but universally known as the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "brother of the Lord",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 9:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Perhaps it was this appearance which made him become decided for the cause and service of his divine brother. Comp. Michaelis on our passage. The apocryphal narrative of the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Evang. sec. Hebr",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". in Jerome, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "de vir. ill",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". 2, is, even as regards time, here irrelevant (in opposition to Grotius).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τοῖς ἀποστόλοις πᾶσιν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀπόστολοι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", since it takes in James also (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Galatians 1:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), must stand here in a wider sense than ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ΤΟῖς ΔΏΔΕΚΑ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "ΤΟῖς ΔΏΔΕΚΑ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but includes them ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "along with",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " others. In the Book of Acts, Barnabas, for instance, is called an apostle (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 14:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 14:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Thessalonians 2:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Timothy and Silvanus are comprehended under the conception ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀπόστολοι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", of whom, of course, Timothy at least cannot be as yet included here. Chrysostom supposes the Seventy to be included. Comp. on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 12:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In no case is it simply the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Twelve",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " again who are meant, whom Hofmann conceives to be designated here in their relation to the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "church",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". How arbitrary that is, and how superfluous such a designation would be! But ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "πᾶσι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " stands decidedly opposed to it; Paul would have required to write ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ΕἾΤΑ ΠΆΛΙΝ ΤΟῖς ἈΠΟΣΤ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "ΕἾΤΑ ΠΆΛΙΝ ΤΟῖς ἈΠΟΣΤ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Notice also the strict marking off of the original apostles by ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ΟἹ ΔΏΔΕΚΑ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "ΟἹ ΔΏΔΕΚΑ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", an expression which Paul uses ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in no other place",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "[30] Comp. Plitt in the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Zeitschrift f. Luth. Theol",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". 1864, p. 28 ff.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
